%We compare four formulations of animal movement HMMs using fisher ({\it Pekania pennanti}) location data \citep[][]{brown2012accelerometer} originally examined by \cite{lapoint2013animal,lapoint2013data} and analyzed compulsively by statisticians ever since \citep[e.g.,][]{SignerEtAl2019,FiebergEtAl2021,hodel2022circular,FiebergEtAl2024}. Using the subset of six individuals that was examined by \cite{hodel2022circular}, we fit a suite 2- and 3-state models including: 1) the standard step and turn HMM (``STorig''; Eqs \ref{eq:steps}--\ref{eq:HMMlike}); 2) the standard step and turn HMM with $\theta_s=0$ for $s \in \{1,\ldots,N\}$ (``ST''); 3) the correlated step and turn model (``crwST''; Eqs \ref{eq:ricesteps}--\ref{eq:vmangles}); 4) the correlated random walk in the Cartesian plane (``crwpos''; Eq.\ \ref{eq:crw}); 5) the reparameterized discrete-time approximation of the continuous-time correlated random walk (Eq.\ \ref{eq:disApprox}) with $\Delta_t=1$ (``crw''); and 6) the reparameterized correlated random walk (Eq.\ \ref{eq:disApprox}) using the actual time steps $\Delta_t \approx 10$mins (``ctcrw''). While these data are commonly treated as a discrete time series, the actual $\Delta_t$ range from 9--11mins, so this provides an opportunity to compare discrete- and continuous-time formulations. Common metrics for assessing HMM goodness-of-fit include information criteria such as AIC or BIC, pseudo-residual plots, quantile-quantile (q-q) plots of the pseudo-residuals, and autocorrelation plots of the pseudo-residuals \citep{ZucchiniEtAl2016,pohle2017selecting}. We therefore focus on these metrics here, as well as how data simulated from the various fitted models compares with the original data (see Fig.\ S9 in Supporting Information). Model fitting, assessment, and simulation were performed using R package \verb|momentuHMM| version 2.0.0 \citep{McClintockMichelot2018}, with data and code for reproducing the analysis available in McClintock (2025).

%None of the various models captured all of the variation or patterns in the data, but this allows us to highlight what each model appears to do well (and not so well). Among the step and turn models, both AIC and BIC overwhelmingly favored the 3-state correlated step and turn model (``crwST3''), followed in distant second by the 2-state correlated step and turn model (``crwST2''; Table \ref{tab:fisherSelectST}). 

%The ``crwpos3'' model identified three fairly distinct movement behavior states consisting of short steps directed away from the previous movement direction ($\beta_1=-0.41$, SE$=XX$; $\sigma_1=2.7$, SE$=XX$), moderate steps in a simple random walk ($\beta_2=-0.01$, SE$=XX$; $\sigma_2=9.8$, SE$=XX$), and long directionally persistent steps ($\beta_3=0.42$, SE$=XX$; $\sigma_3=50.9$, SE$=XX$).

